[6 6 Lara 6] , who earned a stern rebuke from his own tour management after an angry outburst against [7 7 Australia 7] wicketkeeper [8 8 Ian Healy 8] , scored five to prolong a run of poor form with the bat . The [9 9 West Indies 9] vice-captain struggled for timing during his 36-minute stay at the crease before chipping a ball from medium pacer [10 10 Tom Moody 10] straight to [11 11 Shane Warne 11] at mid-wicket . [12 12 West Indies 12] were 53 for two in 15 overs when rain stopped play at the [13 13 Melbourne Cricket Ground 13] after captain [14 14 Courtney Walsh 14] won the toss and elected to bat . [15 15 Lara 15] 's outburst three days ago has clearly turned some of the [16 16 Australian 16] public against him . [21 21 Lloyd 21] did not say what form the discipline would take . [22 22 Lara 22] , who holds the record for the highest score in test and first-class cricket , was unhappy about [23 23 Healy 23] 's role in the incident and questioned whether the ball had carried to the [24 24 Australia 24] keeper . [25 25 Australia 25] went on to win the match at the [26 26 Sydney Cricket Ground 26] by 124 runs to take a two-nil lead in the five-test series after [27 27 Lara 27] failed in both innings . [28 28 Lara 28] has yet to score a century since [29 29 West Indies 29] arrived in [3 2 Australia 3] five weeks ago . Both [30 30 West Indies 30] and [31 31 Australia 31] team management have played down the incident , stressing that relations between the two sides have not been adversely affected .  [1 1 POLAND 1] GOT MONEY FROM POST-WAR [2 2 SWISS 2] ACCOUNTS . Marcin Grajewski [3 3 WARSAW 3] 1996-12-06 [4 4 Poland 4] said on Friday that [5 5 Swiss 5] bank accounts , which in many cases belonged to [6 6 Polish 6] [7 7 Jews 7] who died in the [8 8 Holocaust 8] , were used in debt settlements between the two countries after the [9 9 World War Two 9] . Foreign Minister [10 10 Dariusz Rosati 10] , unveiling first findings of a special government commission , said that in 1970s the then communist [11 11 Poland 11] received 460,000 [12 12 Swiss 12] francs from the accounts . " In 1970s , [13 13 Poland 13] received from unclaimed accounts in [14 14 Switzerland 14] a sum of 460,000 francs . What was its right ( to the money ) ...I do not know , " [15 15 Rosati 15] told a news conference . [16 16 Switzerland 16] stands accused by Senator Alfonse D'Amato , chairman of the powerful U.S. Senate Banking Committee , of agreeing to give money to [17 17 Poland 17] from unclaimed bank accounts of [18 18 Polish 18] citizens , as part of an accord on compensating [19 19 Swiss 19] nationals whose assets had been seized in communist [20 20 Poland 20] . Many of these citizens were [21 21 Jews 21] murdered during the war , when [1 1 Nazi 2 German 1] invaders killed most of [22 22 Poland 22] 's 3.5 million [23 23 Jews 23] . [24 24 Rosati 24] did not say whether the payment in 1970s was part of the 1949 agreement between [25 25 Warsaw 25] and [26 26 Switzerland 26] on compensation to [27 27 Swiss 27] citizens whose assets were seized by the Soviet-imposed communists authorities after [28 28 World War Two 28] . " I expect that the commission will finish gathering information within two to three weeks and then more details will be provided , " [29 29 Rosati 29] said . [30 30 Rosati 30] confirmed that the 1949 agreement had provided for granting [31 31 Switzerland 31] about 53 million francs and most of this sum was repaid with coal exports . He said , however , that [32 32 Switzerland 32] did get about 16,000 francs from the so-called " dead accounts " as part of the compensation . " About 16,000 francs were seized from accounts of four or five [33 33 Polish 33] citizens , whose data we do not precisely know . The issue is of moral and legal nature , because its financial significance is small , " [34 34 Rosati 34] said . Under pressure from international [35 35 Jewish 35] organisations , [36 36 Swiss 36] government has devised a plan to pay out millions of dollars in unclaimed bank accounts as a conciliatory gesture toward [37 37 Holocaust 37] victims . The conservative Radical Democrats ( [2 3 FDP 2] ) have said they would ask parliament next week to order [38 38 Swiss 38] banks to put some 40 million [39 39 Swiss 39] francs ( $ 31 million ) in dormant wealth into a fund earmarked for [40 40 Jewish 40] groups and charitable organisations . But [41 41 Swiss 41] banks and the country 's [42 42 Jewish 42] community voiced doubts whether the plan would work .

Trade and Industry Secretary [8 8 Ian Lang 8] added that even if the conditions were met by both airlines , final clearance would hinge on an open skies deal between [9 9 Britain 9] and the [10 10 United States 10] to liberalise trans-Atlantic air traffic , which would create greater competition on the routes . [1 Lang 1] said he supported conditions proposed by [11 11 Britain 11] 's [12 12 Office of Fair Trading 12] , which was asked to examine the case last month . " I agree ... that without suitable undertakings the alliance would be likely to lead to a significant loss of actual and potential passengers , on those routes where BA and AA currently compete and for all passengers on the trans-Atlantic market route between the UK and [13 13 U.S. 13] , " he said . The conditions for clearance of the alliance were that [15 15 British Airways 15] and [16 16 American 16] drop 168 slots at [17 17 London Heathrow 17] airport , the busiest in [18 18 Europe 18] . [19 19 American 19] 's parent , [20 20 AMR Corp. 20] , said it did not view the terms as a " deal breaker . " However , it called the conditions " more severe " than those imposed by other regulatory authorities on similar airline alliances . [21 21 British Airways 21] 's initial response was that " unconditional divestiture of slots is unprecedented and if done it must be on the basis of fair market value . " It added that it would be " prepared to take reasonable steps to assist the introduction of additional competition . " The government also wants [22 22 British Airways 22] to drop a clause in its agreement with [23 23 USAir 23] that bars it from competing on trans-Atlantic routes , and said both [24 24 British Airways 24] and [25 25 American 25] should be prepared to reduce services on the [26 26 London 26] to [2 Dallas-Fort Worth 2] route in the event that a new entrant wishes to enter . It also suggested losing some slots on the London-to-Boston route . The [27 27 Office of Fair Trade 27] called for [28 28 British Airways 28] / [29 29 American 29] to allow third-party access to their joint frequent flyer programme where the applicant does not have access to an equivalent programme . [3 Lang 3] said responses should be made to the 2 Office of Fair Trading by Jan. 10 , 1997 .

 1 NYC Jan refunding has its 1st Euro floating rate . [1 1 NEW YORK 1] 1996-12-06 [2 2 New York City 2] on Friday said that it planned a $ 775 million refunding for January that will include its first floating rate issue of taxable debt for [3 3 European 3] investors . A city official , who declined to be named , explained that [1 Goldman , Sachs 1] , which this summer was demoted to the second tier of the syndicate , proposed the floating rate issue and as a result was promoted to book runner for this offering . By selling the floating rate debt , the city hopes to establish a benchmark , the city official said , adding that it needed a large deal to accomplish this objective . The city in late June sold its first issue of Euronotes , a strategy that it says saved it $ 500,000 in interest costs , and it has been trying to build on this strategy of expanding the pool of potential investors since then . In November , [4 4 New York City 4] said it became the first [5 5 U.S. 5] municipality to offer bonds for sale in [6 6 European 6] markets by competitive bidding as it listed taxable bonds on the [7 7 London Stock Exchange 7] . The refunding planned for January also includes a $ 475 million tax-exempt offering . No specific date in January has been selected for the debt sale , the official added . -- Joan Gralla , 212-859-1654

Sample: b'1238testb_Wall'
 [1 Wall St 1] speculates about [2 Santa Fe 2] savior . Brendan Intindola [1 1 NEW YORK 1] 1996-12-06 Homestake Mining Co tops [2 2 Wall Street 2] 's list as the most likely white knight buyer for Santa Fe Pacific Gold Corp if Santa Fe rejects unsolicited suitor [3 Newmont Mining Corp 3] . Santa Fe is so far mum on the more than $ 2 billion stock swap takeover proposal from [3 3 Newmont 3] , announced Thursday . [4 1 Wall Street 4] , since the bid , has speculated that any deal between [4 4 Newmont 4] and Santa Fe would be a " bear hug , " or a reluctantly negotiated agreement where the buyer is not necessarily a friendly suitor . [5 5 Newmont 5] said the companies have had previous contact , though declined to detail the encounters . Analysts predict [5 Santa Fe 5] will go to the highest bidder , and that if a rival buyer is found , [6 6 Newmont 6] may not be able to match its offer . They said the [6 Santa Fe 6] deal , which includes desirable [7 7 Nevada 7] mining territory , would only payoff for [8 8 Newmont 8] longer term . [9 9 Newmont 9] , in fact , will not benefit from the [7 Santa Fe 7] acquisition on an earnings basis for at least two years , which also limits its capacity to raise its offer . Any deal , friendly or hostile , would almost assuredly be a stock swap , which is necessary to preserve the tax-free , pooling-of-interest accounting , they said . Analysts and arbitrageurs immediately ruled out Barrick Gold Corp and [8 Bre-X Minerals Ltd 8] as Santa Fe saviors because they are locked in negotiations over their splitting [10 10 Indonesia 10] 's Busang vast gold deposit . [9 Placer Dome Inc 9] too was considered unlikley because it is focusing on geographic expansion in areas that do match [10 Santa Fe 10] 's [11 11 Nevada 11] , [12 12 South America 12] and [13 13 Central Asia 13] presence , they said . A [11 Homestake 11] spokesman was not immediately available to comment on speculation that it tops the list . [12 Homestake 12] , based in [14 14 San Francisco 14] , operates gold mines in the [15 15 United States 15] , [16 16 Australia 16] , [17 17 Chile 17] and [18 18 Canada 18] . Earnings in 1995 were $ 0.22 per share , or $ 30.3 million , on revenues of $ 746.3 million . Santa Fe is headquartered [19 19 Albuquerque 19] , [20 20 N.M. 20] and reported 1995 earnings of $ 0.30 per share , or $ 40 million , on revenues of $ 350 million . Santa Fe has mining and exploration operations in [21 21 Nevada 21] , [22 22 California 22] , [23 23 Montana 23] , [24 24 Canada 24] , [25 25 Brazil 25] , [26 26 Australia 26] , [27 27 Chile 27] , [28 28 Kazakstan 28] , [13 2 Mexico 13] and [29 29 Ghana 29] . [30 30 PaineWebber 30] analyst Marc Cohen said he lowered his rating on [31 31 Newmont 31] to neutral from attractive today because if [32 32 Newmont 32] merged with Santa Fe , investors would have to wait until the second half of 1998 to realize earnings accretion . " I think [14 Homestake 14] could come in as a white knight , but how much is someone willing to come in above the [33 33 Newmont 33] number . One would have to outbid by at least 15 percent , but there is going to be a ( [15 Santa Fe 15] ) deal with someone , " he said . " Longer term , two to three years out , ( a Newmont-Santa Fe deal ) is positive , it does all the right things . But in the near-term it is , at worst , neutral , " the analyst added . [34 34 Newmont 34] proposed to Santa Fe a stock-swap merger at a ratio of 0.33 [35 35 Newmont 35] shares for each [16 Santa Fe 16] shares . In Friday [36 36 New York Stock Exchange 36] trade , Newmonth was off 1/2 to 46-5/8 while Santa Fe added 1/4 to 15-1/8 . " [37 37 Newmont 37] said it wants to discuss a friendly deal with [17 Santa Fe 17] , which is almost always a euphemism for ' We have more money in our pocket , ' " said an arb , referring to a possible sweetened bid from [38 38 Newmont 38] . Jonathan Wright [2 2 NAIROBI 2] 1996-12-06 The [3 3 Canadian 3] general in charge of a multinational force for eastern [4 4 Zaire 4] said on Friday he was going back to [5 5 Zaire 5] for more information about the plight of about 165,000 [6 6 Rwandan 6] refugees adrift in the countryside . Lieutenant-General [7 7 Maurice Baril 7] told a news conference in [8 8 Nairobi 8] his main concern was for a large group of about 150,000 refugees living off the land in a valley about 65 km ( 40 miles ) west of the eastern city of [9 9 Goma 9] . If he decided it was necessary and safe for the aircrew , he would not hesitate to order airdrops of food for the refugees , even against the wishes of the government in [10 10 Kinshasa 10] and the [11 11 Zairean 11] rebels who control much of eastern [12 12 Zaire 12] , he said . " Tomorrow I 'm going into [13 13 Rwanda 13] and my intention is to go across into eastern [14 14 Zaire 14] and try to find out for the second time what the situation is on the ground , " he said . General [15 15 Baril 15] saw rebel leader [16 16 Laurent Kabila 16] in [17 17 Goma 17] last week but the rebels told him the crisis was over because most of the [18 18 Rwandan 18] refugees have already gone home . The rebels do not want the multinational force to deploy on the ground , for fear it might help the [19 19 Zairean 19] army regain control of the area . [20 20 Kinshasa 20] opposes airdrops , apparently because the food could fall into the hands of the rebels and their local supporters . " It does n't look as though they ( airdrops ) are going to be required in any significant way because the [1 NGOs 1] ( non-governmental organisations ) are in that area on the border between [22 22 Zaire 22] and [23 23 Rwanda 23] , " 2 Young told reporters . " We hope that if the front moves forward or stabilises then we will have access ( to the large group of refugees ) with reconnaissance or humanitarian agencies . And my mandate is also under Chapter Seven to operate in eastern [26 26 Zaire 26] . " Under Chapter Seven of the [27 27 U.N. 27] charter , the [28 28 Security Council 28] has wide powers to preserve peace and security . The former minister and his son had been taken from their home close to the presidential palace , which is guarded by loyalist soldiers backed by [12 12 French 12] troops based in [13 13 Bangui 13] . Sample: b'1259testb_Plastic'
 Plastic surgery gets boost in [1 1 Brazil 1] . Simona de Logu [2 2 RIO DE JANEIRO 2] 1996-12-06 Plastic surgery is booming , especially among men , as [3 3 Brazilians 3] spend much of their new-found wealth on the latest beauty treatments , said the organisers of a four-day international plastic surgery conference that opened on Friday . The number of plastic surgeries in [4 4 Brazil 4] has jumped 30 percent to an estimated 150,000 this year since an anti-inflation plan was introduced in July 1994 , Farid Hakme , the president of the Brazilian Plastic Surgery Society ( SBCP ) , said . The number of operations on men increased even more -- by 80 percent , from 8,000 in 1994 to 15,000 in 1995 , he said . " [5 5 Brazil 5] ranks right at the top for plastic surgery with respect to the number of surgeons , the number of patients , number of operations , number of conferences . Our statistics are the highest for everything , " Hakme said . " We believe the increase in plastic surgeries for men results from the difficulties in the job market . People need to have a more youthful look to compete in the job market , given the profound changes in [6 6 Latin America 6] 's economy . " A controlled exchange rate , trade liberalisation and tight monetary policies have also dramatically curbed inflation , making more money available for cosmetic surgery . [7 7 Brazil 7] has been at the forefront in plastic surgery for decades and is home to one of the most famous surgeons , Ivo Pitangy . There are 6,000 plastic surgeons there , of which 4,500 have qualified to be members of the SBCP . Every year , 500 new plastic surgeons graduate in [8 8 Brazil 8] and medical students from all over the world come to study there . Hakme attributes [9 9 Brazil 9] 's fascination with plastic surgery not to excessive vanity but to the country 's mix and match of different races , which can create physical disharmonies . " What happens is the nose sometimes does n't match the mouth or the buttocks do n't match with the legs , " he said . [10 10 Brazil 10] 's most sought-after beauty treatment is liposuction in which fat is sucked away from areas of the body , with about 30,000 operations a year at a cost of $ 3,000 to $ 4,000 each . Stomach tucks and breast operations are also popular since the tropical climate calls for flesh-baring fashions , but unlike women elsewhere [11 11 Brazilians 11] tend to have breast reductions and buttock implants . " The women who want to reduce their breasts here would probably want to increase them in the [12 12 United States 12] , " SBCP Vice-President Oswaldo Saldanha said . " Beauty ideals and cultures are different in every country . " Plastic surgery scares like the case in which [13 13 Brazilian 13] model Claudia Liz fell into a coma after being anaesthetised for a liposuction in October are not much of a deterrent . Saldanha said operations fell 30 percent immediately after that case but the rate was back to normal now .

" I sincerely believe that this unfortunate choice in giving the honour to such a controversial figure as [22 22 Ramos Horta 22] ... will exacerbate the problem in finding a solution ( to [23 23 East Timor 23] ) , " [24 24 Alatas 24] said on Friday . He was responding to questions at a news conference called to discuss next week 's ministerial meeting of the [25 25 Organisation of the Islamic Conference 25] ( [26 26 OIC 26] ) in [27 27 Jakarta 27] . [28 28 Ramos Horta 28] has been a vocal leader of the opposition to [3 Jakarta 3] 's rule in the territory . [29 29 Belo 29] and [30 30 Ramos Horta 30] were awared the prize for their efforts to secure a peaceful solution to the issue of [31 31 East Timor 31] , a former [32 32 Portuguese 32] colony which [33 33 Indonesia 33] invaded in 1975 and annexed the following year . The [34 34 United Nations 34] has never recognised [4 Jakarta 4] 's move . [35 35 Alatas 35] said the government 's position on the [36 36 Nobel Peace Prize 36] would have been different if it had been awarded solely to [37 37 Belo 37] . Asked if the [38 38 Indonesian 38] ambassador to [39 39 Norway 39] would have attended the ceremony if only [40 40 Belo 40] had been involved , [41 41 Alatas 41] replied : " Probably , yes , but that is a hypothetical question . " [42 42 Alatas 42] said on Tuesday that on his way back from [43 43 Oslo 43] , [44 44 Belo 44] would visit the [5 3 Vatican 5] to see the [6 Pope 6] , and would also meet [45 45 German 45] Chancellor [46 46 Helmut Kohl 46] in [47 47 Bonn 47] . [1 1 RANGOON 1] 1996-12-07 [2 2 Burmese 2] troops and riot police moved in to disperse a student street protest at a suburban road junction near the Ranyon ( [1 Rangoon 1] ) University early on Saturday , witnesses said .  [1 1 Burmese 1] students march briefly out of campus . Vithoon Amorn [2 2 RANGOON 2] 1996-12-06 About 200 [3 3 Burmese 3] students marched briefly from troubled [4 4 Yangon Institute of Technology 4] in northern [5 5 Rangoon 5] on Friday towards the [6 6 University of Yangon 6] six km ( four miles ) away , and returned to their campus , witnesses said . Seven truckloads of armed riot police and three fire engines were on standby at one of the junctions near the institute . There were no clashes . " They are now back in the [1 YIT 1] campus , " an institute official who declined to be identified told [7 7 Reuters 7] by telephone . One of two roads leading to the [8 8 University of Yangon 8] from the institute had been closed by authorities . But about 300 university students were still gathered outside the gates of their campus , witnesses said . They were singing peacefully . On Monday and Tuesday , students from the institute and the university launched protests against what they said was unfair handling by police of a brawl between some of their colleagues and restaurant owners in October . On Tuesday and Wednesday , opposition leader [9 9 Aung San Suu Kyi 9] was restricted to her home by the military government to prevent her from being drawn into the protests . She was allowed to move freely on Thursday . The protest culminated at dawn on Tuesday with several hundred students being detained briefly by police in central [10 10 Rangoon 10] . The street protests were the biggest seen in the capital since the student-led pro-democracry demonstrations of September 1988 when the junta crushed the uprising . Thousands were killed or imprisoned . Earlier on Friday some of the students , who were held briefly by police during the protests earlier this week , said they were still dissatisfied with the military government . They told [11 11 Reuters 11] they were unhappy that the ruling [2 State Law and Order Restoration Council 2] ( [3 SLORC 3] ) had not heeded their calls for the right to organise independent unions on campus . " We still want government answers to our demands . We want police punishment to be published in newspapers , " one student said . But the students stressed their protests were non-political and they had no contact with [12 12 Suu Kyi 12] 's [13 13 National League for Democracy 13] ( 1 NLD ) . [14 14 Suu Kyi 14] , a [4 2 Nobel 4] laureate and daughter of independence hero [5 3 Aung San 5] , and key [15 15 NLD 15] officials have also denied any link with the students . But they have said both parties had a " moral link " in that they were against police brutality and injustice . The students also demanded the government announce punishments meted out to policemen who they said had manhandled students involved in a brawl with some restaurant owners near the [16 16 Yangon 16] institute in October . The students appealed to the government not to close the institute because of their latest demonstration . The institute was shut for nearly two years after the 1988 uprising . On Friday , the road leading to [17 17 Suu Kyi 17] 's lakeside residence in central [18 18 Rangoon 18] remained closed by police .

The three-day trade union conference in [14 14 Singapore 14] hopes to push labour issues onto the [15 15 WTO 15] agenda . [3 Jordan 3] said the [16 16 WTO 16] 's credibility was at stake over the issue of trade and labour . The [17 17 ICFTU 17] said it wanted the [18 18 WTO 18] conference beginning on Monday to outlaw forced and child labour , end discrimination in hiring , and guarantee the right to join a union . [23 23 ASEAN 23] groups [24 24 Brunei 24] , [25 25 Indonesia 25] , [26 26 Malaysia 26] , the [27 27 Philippines 27] , [28 28 Singapore 28] , [29 29 Thailand 29] and [30 30 Vietnam 30] .  [1 1 Indian 1] rubber demand seen outstripping production . [2 2 SINGAPORE 2] 1996-12-06 [3 3 Indian 3] rubber demand is seen outpacing local production in the 1996/97 April / March season and the trend will persist way into the next century , the chairman of the Rubber Board of India said on Friday . K.J. Matthew said at the Asia Rubber Markets meeting here [4 4 Indian 4] production of natural rubber in 1996/97 will reach 547,000 tonnes against projected demand of 578,000 tonnes , a gap of 31,000 tonnes . For synthetic rubber , production reached 68,200 tonnes in 1995/96 while consumption in the same season hit 134,085 tonnes , Matthew added . " Though schemes designed to realise further increases in the production of natural rubber are being operated successfully , the demand-supply gap is expected to widen , " he said . [5 5 Indian 5] synthetic rubber output is not expected to rise significantly in the next season but demand will rise to 145,000 tonnes . Matthew estimates that by the 2000/01 season , the gap between natural rubber output and consumption will rise to 51,000 tonnes and 319,000 tonnes in 2010/11 . Natural rubber production will go up to 695,000 tonnes in 2000/01 against consumption of 746,000 tonnes . In 2010/11 , domestic demand should rise further to 1.233 million tonnes while production will only reach about 914,000 tonnes . One way to bridge the widening gap is to put more land under cultivation which the 1 Rubber Board official estimates will reach 220,000 hectares between now and the year 2003 although Matthew said this may not be possible at this time in [6 6 India 6] . " The development objective for the rubber plantation industry will be to increase production to the best extent possibly with a view to minimising imports of natural rubber , " he said . -- Singapore Newsroom ( 65-8703305 )

 [1 1 Japan 1] 's authorities seen seeking to rein in dollar . George Nishiyama [2 2 TOKYO 2] 1996-12-06 Comments by [3 3 Japan 3] 's tight-lipped central bank chief and an influential top bureaucrat are further signs that the nation 's authorities want to keep the dollar at current levels , market sources said on Friday . In a rare expression of a view on currencies by the [4 4 Bank of Japan 4] ( [5 5 BOJ 5] ) governor , [1 Yasuo Matsushita 1] was quoted in [6 6 Japan 6] 's leading economic daily on Friday as saying that he sees no further , immediate fall in the yen . This followed a widely watched television appearance late on Thursday by Eisuke Sakakibara , a high-ranking 1 Finance Ministry official , who denied he had said he wants to guide the dollar lower to between 108 and 110 yen . But many in the market thought Sakakibara 's real intentions lay elsewhere , and took more notice of his comments about the [7 7 U.S. 7] government 's stance on the dollar , dealers said . " I think his views on ( [8 8 U.S. Treasury 8] Secretary 2 Robert ) [9 9 Rubin 9] 's comments were indeed what he himself thinks about the dollar , " said Hank Note , chief dealer at [10 10 Sumitomo Bank 10] . Asked about [11 11 Rubin 11] 's comment that a strong dollar was in [12 12 U.S. 12] interests , Sakakibara said the remark does not necessarily mean the [13 13 United States 13] supports a stronger dollar . " It 's a strong dollar , not stronger . In that sense , the comments are not pointing to a certain direction , " he said . " It shows that Sakakibara is not for a stronger dollar either , " said [14 14 Sumitomo 14] 's Note . Takao Sakoh , first vice president at [15 15 Union Bank of Switzerland 15] in [16 16 Tokyo 16] , said : " Maybe a dollar at 104.50 yen is not acceptable ( to Sakakibara ) , but it may be okay at the current level , at the lower end of 112 yen . " Market participants have kept a close eye on Sakakibara , chief of the ministry 's International Finance Bureau , as a comment he made in November after the dollar hit this year 's high of 114.92 yen pushed the currency down sharply . He had said then that the market 's view on [17 17 Japan 17] 's economy was too pessimistic and that he believed it was stronger than the market thought . Dealers have come to refer to 115 yen as the " Sakakibara ceiling " for the dollar following the remark . Adding to the comments by " Mr Yen " , as Sakakibara is known for his prominence in the currency market , was [18 18 BOJ 18] governor [2 Matsushita 2] 's remark . " The recent level of the yen exchange rate has been stable , and it does not appear to be moving towards a further depreciation of the yen immediately , so import prices are likely to stabilise at current levels , " Matsushita said in an interview with the [19 19 Nihon Keizai Shimbun 19] . " The fact that he touched on the issue of inflation triggered by import prices shows that the [20 20 BOJ 20] does not want a further depreciation of the yen , past 115 yen , " said Yasuhito Kawashima , chief forex manager at Toyo Trust & Banking Co . Some said the central bank may have been concerned a weaker yen would lead to unfounded pessimism about [21 21 Japan 21] 's economy . " There was concern that foreign investors may sell [22 22 Japanese 22] stocks if the dollar goes above 115 yen . The [23 23 BOJ 23] does not want the yen 's weakness to lead to pessimism over the economy , " said Taisuke Tanaka , market strategist with [24 24 Credit Suisse 24] in [25 25 Tokyo 25] . Senior [26 26 BOJ 26] officials have separately said financial markets ' views on the economy have been too negative . " I realise there are negative views in the markets about the impact of the consumption tax hike and drop in public spending , but the markets appear to be exaggerating the magnitude of the negative impact , " a senior [27 27 BOJ 27] official told [28 28 Reuters 28] on Friday . The consumption tax is due to raised in April from three to five percent .

[1 1 TALLAHASSEE 1] , Fla. 1996-12-06 Fourteen years after he bludgeoned and shot a man whose trailer home he robbed in 1982 , John Mills Jr . , 41 , was put to death in Florida 's electric chair Friday . As Glenn Lawhon , a rural Florida minister who is the victim 's father , looked on , Mills was pronounced dead at 7:13 a.m. EST ( 1213 [2 2 GMT 2] ) for the murder of Lester Lawhon . Speaking in [3 3 Arabic 3] , Mills made a final statement before an anonymous citizen flipped the switch that sent 2000 volts of electricity through his body , said Department of Corrections spokesman Eugene Morris , who was present at the execution . [1 Mills 1] is the 38th person to die in [2 Florida 2] 's electric chair since the [9 9 U.S. Supreme Court 9] reversed itself in 1976 and legalised the death penalty . Sample: b'1285testb_Half'
 Half of dog bites provoked , says [1 1 American 1] vet . [2 2 CHICAGO 2] 1996-12-06 As many as 1 million dog bites are recorded in the [3 3 United States 3] every year and half of them are provoked by humans , a veterinarian told fellow animal doctors on Friday . The [1 Humane Society of the 1 United States 1] estimates that between 500,000 and one million bites are delivered by dogs each year , more than half of which are suffered by children . " Most bites can be prevented by teaching children how to respect a dog , " Michael Cornwell of the Glencoe Animal Hospital in [4 4 Columbus 4] , [5 5 Ohio 5] , told the annual meeting of the [6 6 American Veterinary Medical Association 6] . " Let 's not let our kids jump on them or crawl on them . Dogs and children do n't have to have an interaction . Let 's respect their territories , " he said . Cornwell said 50 percent of reported bites were provoked by a person and 60 percent were suffered by children . He also estimated that only 25 percent of bites were reported because medical attention was not needed . Don Rieck , president of the National Animal Control Association , said aggressiveness in dogs was related more to gender than breed and a male dog that had not been neutered was three times more likely to bite than an unspayed female . The five breeds credited with the most incidents were chow chows , [2 Rottweilers 2] , [3 2 German 3] shepherds , cocker spaniels and [4 3 Dalmatians 4] . " The trends in dog bites by particular breeds have more to do with fad pets owned by individuals who need to have something unique . Speaking strictly of dogs , 15 years ago the macho fad pet was a [7 7 Doberman 7] . Today , [5 Rottweilers 5] are on the way up , " Rieck said . If approached by a stray dog , children should be taught to stand still with fists folded underneath the neck , elbows in , and gaze forward until the dog goes away .

 EU , [1 1 Poland 1] agree on oil import tariffs . [2 2 BRUSSELS 2] 1996-12-06 The [3 3 European Union 3] and [4 4 Poland 4] have resolved disagreements over a new [5 5 Polish 5] oil import regime , the [6 6 European Commission 6] said on Friday . The EU had objected to increases in [7 7 Polish 7] tariffs on imports of gasoline and gasoil products introduced on January 1 , 1996 , saying they contravened levels envisaged in the so-called [1 1 Europe Agreement 1] between the EU and [8 8 Poland 8] . The increases were aimed at protecting the [9 9 Polish 9] market while helping to modernise the local oil industry . " The EU and [10 10 Poland 10] have now reached a final settlement regarding issues related to the [11 11 Polish 11] import regime in the oils sector , " the [12 12 Commission 12] said in a statement . Under the agreement , [13 13 Poland 13] will abolish all oil import tariffs by 2001 , remove all oil price controls and end quantitative restrictions on imports by January 1 , 1997 . The agreement includes the early privatisation and modernisation of [14 14 Polish 14] oil refineries , which will be obliged to offer equal treatment to all buyers . The EU and [15 15 Poland 15] will monitor the settlement at six-monthly meetings .

 Cyberspace squabbles overshadow copyright talks . Elif Kaban [1 1 GENEVA 1] 1996-12-06 In a gloomy [2 2 Geneva 2] conference centre built before the dawn of the [3 3 Internet 3] , groups of staid officials made a first stab on Friday at rewriting copyright laws for the digital age . But critics at the first government-level meeting to revise copyright laws in 25 years said the officials and legislators might as well be trying to police the ether . After four days of diplomatic wrangling over procedures , some 600 delegates from nations small and large got down to the nitty-gritty of setting the digital agenda for the first time . Cyberspace squabbles overshadowed the debate on a stack of proposals covering literary and artistic works , the rights of performers and producers of music and producers of databases . " If it goes on like this , we wo n't have enough time to finish all the discussions , " a frustrated [1 Western 1] delegate said . " They announced they will start evening sessions next week . " Attempts by copyright-based industries to ensure they get a cut from online works led to a storm of protests by [4 4 Internet 4] companies and critics who say the pacts would curb public access to online information from soccer results to stock prices . " It 's not illegal to make photocopies of newspaper articles . It 's fair use . We can read sports statistics or stock prices . But with the treaty , this kind of fact will be owned and subject to licensing , " said James Love , a consumer lobbyist heading the Washington-based Consumer Project on Technology . " None of the treaties are ready to move . These people do n't understand what they 're doing . " At stake are billions of dollars and the future of the electronic information industry -- the coming medium for the distribution of music , films , literature , software and commerce . Supporters of the three pacts say they are only an extension of existing intellectual property rights , covered by the century-old [2 Berne Convention 2] . But an array of opponents from the network industry to consumer , scientific and academic groups say the pacts will give sweeping powers to entertainment and copyright-based industries . A quick survey at the conference centre found few officials who had actually surfed the [5 5 Internet 5] . [6 6 Mongolia 6] 's state copyright official , Gundegma Jargalshaihan , said apologetically that he had just arrived from [7 7 Ulan Bator 7] and was not aware of the details of the digital agenda . " We do n't have money for [8 8 Internet 8] in [9 9 Mongolia 9] , " he added . Alexander Bavykin , deputy legal chief at [10 10 Russia 10] 's foreign ministry , said 1 Moscow had yet to formulate a policy on copyright in cybersppace . He too had never browsed the Net . " I 've never tried it and why should I ? There are lots of other things in this life I have n't tried either , " he said . A visit to the computer centre offering [11 11 Internet 11] services found a lone [12 12 European 12] official clicking away on his mouse . " [13 13 Internet 13] is a potential cash cow for copyright-based industries and we need roadmaps on the information superhighway , " said Marc Pearl , vice-president of the 2 Information Technology Association of America , a trade association of [14 14 U.S. 14] network companies opposing the treaties . " But there are a lot of dinosaurs here . People here do n't understand [15 15 Internet 15] technology . Because they do n't understand technology , they fear the unknown . " Before the [16 16 Internet 16] , those whose business was to protect copyrights knew where they stood . Their enemies were tangible if elusive , such as the people who pirated music cassettes . But the [17 17 Internet 17] , a global computer network where anything from music to software can be duplicated and distributed at the click of a computer mouse , has ripped up the rulebooks . Network operators said the draft laws would hold them responsible for copyright infringements in the system and expose them to multi-billion-dollar liabilities . " There are 500 million messages transmitted through the [18 18 Internet 18] everyday , " said Tim Casey of the 3 U.S.-based [19 19 MCI Communications Corporation 19] . " How can we control them all ? "

Sample: b'1341testb_FEATURE'
 FEATURE - [1 1 Singapore 1] sees prestige in hosting [2 2 WTO 2] . Ramthan Hussain [3 3 SINGAPORE 3] 1996-12-06 [4 4 Singapore 4] 's winning campaign to host the [5 5 World Trade Organisation 5] ( [6 6 WTO 6] ) 's first ministerial meeting reflected its ambition to play a key role in shaping global free trade , the lifeblood of its economy , analysts said . " As one of the world 's most externally oriented economies , [7 7 Singapore 7] has a disproportionately large stake in the [8 8 WTO 8] , " said Desmond Supple , economist at research house I.D.E.A . " [9 9 Singapore 9] stands to benefit more than most from continued global trade liberalisation as trade is the engine of its growth , accounting for nearly three times its gross domestic product . " The city-state met [10 10 U.S. 10] opposition two years ago in its bid to host the meeting , expected to gather 4,000 officials from 160 countries from December 9 to 13 . In a stand some analysts linked to controversy over [11 11 Singapore 11] 's caning of an [12 12 American 12] teenager for vandalism , then-U.S. Trade Representative [13 13 Mickey Kantor 13] had said the meeting ought to be held where the [14 14 WTO 14] was going to be headquartered . That would have meant [15 15 Geneva 15] . But [16 16 Singapore 16] had the support of other [17 17 WTO 17] members . Derek da Cunha , senior fellow at the [18 18 Institute of Policy Studies 18] ( ISEAS ) , said [19 19 Singapore 19] 's hosting of the conference " carries a great deal of symbolism for the city-state , underscoring its commitment to free trade and its trading links across the globe . " There is the international prestige [20 20 Singapore 20] would enjoy , but " more importantly there is a genuine national interest in fostering better global free trade and an open market " , said Tan Kong Yam , head of Business Policy at the [21 21 National University of Singapore 21] . At the ministerial meeting , trade ministers will review the work of the [22 22 WTO 22] and the implementation of the [1 1 Uruguay Round 1] free trade commitments under its predecessor the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade ( [2 GATT 2] ) . In June , the [23 23 WTO 23] hailed [24 24 Singapore 24] for its open market policies but the [25 25 European Union 25] and other trading powers called on [26 26 Singapore 26] to speed up the opening of its services sector . Supple said the struggle that [27 27 Singapore 27] had to wage in vying to host the meeting would be repeated during the talks . " There is tension at every step of the way , " since a battle line between the West and developing countries has been drawn over the issue of linking trade liberalisation with labour rights , he said . Supple said hosting the meeting carried prestige for [28 28 Singapore 28] , " however , this is quite intangible as the prestige factor may not necessarily lead to any additional investment and trade flows to this region . " From a commercial point of view , the meeting would be good for [29 29 Singapore 29] 's tourism industry , Tan said . A large part of [30 30 Singapore 30] 's workforce would be mobilised to ensure the meeting would run without a glitch but the average [3 Singaporean 3] " would probably not be too concerned about some of the issues , " Tan said . " But the more educated public will realise that these kind of things are important for [31 31 Singapore 31] as a small economy . " Supple said any political gains the [32 32 Singapore 32] government would get from the [33 33 WTO 33] meeting -- ahead of a general election due by April 1997 -- would depend on how successful it was in pushing its economic agenda . " If there are any movements toward freer trade , then [34 34 Singapore 34] 's economy and the electorate would gain , " he said . " But I do n't think it would be wise to play up the political aspect of this . I think political issues will take secondary importance to all these economic issues that will be displayed . "

[9 9 Woolmer 9] was born in the northern city of [10 10 Kanpur 10] when his father worked there for an insurance compnay and was himself an active cricketer . " It 's been a sentimental journey ... A visit to [11 11 India 11] is always an intriguing experience , " [12 12 Woolmer 12] , now the [13 13 South African 13] coach , said on Saturday . [14 14 Woolmer 14] , 48 , played 19 tests for [15 15 England 15] between 1975 and 1981 . His first cricketing sojurn to [2 2 India 2] was as a member of [16 16 Tony Greig 16] 's [17 17 England 17] side in 1976-77 . His father [18 18 Clarence Woolmer 18] represented 3 United Province , now renamed [19 19 Uttar Pradesh 19] , in [20 20 India 20] 's [21 21 Ranji Trophy 21] national championship and captained the state during 1949 . Now aged 86 , [3 4 Woolmer 3] senior lives with his son in [22 22 Cape Town 22] . [4 5 Woolmer 4] 's memories of [23 23 Kanpur 23] are few and blurred . " I do n't remember much of the place , " he said . " I came here on zero and left at three ( aged three ) when my father was transferred to [24 24 Calcutta 24] where I spent another four and half years . " But I do remember we had a cobra snake in the basement of our house . Also that my father bought a bicycle and when we rode over a hose pipe it broke into two . " [5 6 Woolmer 5] said the hospital where he was born is close to the stadium where the India-South Africa test will be played .

 ALPINE SKIING-OFFICIALS HOPE TO SALVAGE WORLD CUP WEEKEND . [1 1 WHISTLER 1] , [2 2 British Columbia 2] 1996-12-06 1 World Cup ski officials hope to be able to get in at least one men 's downhill training run on Saturday in an effort to salvage the weekend racing programme . For the third consecutive day , Friday 's scheduled training runs were cancelled due to heavy wet snow and fog on [1 2 Whistler Mountain 1] , leaving the scheduled 3 World Cup events in jeopardy . Rules call for at least one training run to be completed before a 4 World Cup downhill race can be staged . Organisers hope to get that run in on Saturday morning , conditions permitting , and stage the race later in the day or on Sunday . " There was no possibility today to make a training run , " said Bernd Zobel , the [2 Canadian 2] men 's national coach , citing too much new snow and poor visibility . If organisers are forced to run the downhill on Sunday , the super-giant slalom originally scheduled for Sunday would likely be abandoned .
